An important application of an infinite direct product is the construction of a projective limit of rings (see below). Another application is a restricted product of a family of rings (cf. adele ring).
Polynomial ring.
Given a symbol "t" (called a variable) and a commutative ring "R", the set of polynomials
forms a commutative ring with the usual addition and multiplication, containing "R" as a subring. It is called the polynomial ring over "R". More generally, the set formula_98 of all polynomials in variables formula_99 forms a commutative ring, containing formula_100 as subrings.
If "R" is an integral domain, then formula_101 is also an integral domain; its field of fractions is the field of rational functions. If "R" is a noetherian ring, then formula_101 is a noetherian ring. If "R" is a unique factorization domain, then formula_101 is a unique factorization domain. Finally, "R" is a field if and only if formula_101 is a principal ideal domain.
Let formula_105 be commutative rings. Given an element "x" of "S", one can consider the ring homomorphism
(i.e., the substitution). If "S"="R"["t"] and "x"="t", then "f"("t")="f". Because of this, the polynomial "f" is often also denoted by formula_107. The image of the map formula_108 is denoted by formula_109; it is the same thing as the subring of "S" generated by "R" and "x".
