Example: let "f" be a polynomial in one variable; i.e., an element in a polynomial ring "R". Then formula_113 is an element in formula_114 and formula_115 is divisible by "h" in that ring. The result of substituting zero to "h" in formula_116 is formula_117, the derivative of "f" at "x".
The substitution is a special case of the universal property of a polynomial ring. The property states: given a ring homomorphism formula_118 and an element "x" in "S" there exists a unique ring homomorphism formula_119 such that formula_120 and formula_121 restricts to formula_122. For example, choosing a basis, a symmetric algebra satisfies the universal property and so is a polynomial ring.
To give an example, let "S" be the ring of all functions from "R" to itself; the addition and the multiplication are those of functions. Let "x" be the identity function. Each "r" in "R" defines a constant function, giving rise to the homomorphism formula_123. The universal property says that this map extends uniquely to
("t" maps to "x") where formula_125 is the polynomial function defined by "f". The resulting map is injective if and only if "R" is infinite.
Given a non-constant monic polynomial "f" in formula_101, there exists a ring "S" containing "R" such that "f" is a product of linear factors in formula_127.
Let "k" be an algebraically closed field. The Hilbert's Nullstellensatz (theorem of zeros) states that there is a natural one-to-one correspondence between the set of all prime ideals in formula_128 and the set of closed subvarieties of formula_129. In particular, many local problems in algebraic geometry may be attacked through the study of the generators of an ideal in a polynomial ring. (cf. Gröbner basis.)
There are some other related constructions. A formal power series ring formula_130 consists of formal power series
together with multiplication and addition that mimic those for convergent series. It contains formula_101 as a subring. Note a formal power series ring does not have the universal property of a polynomial ring; a series may not converge after a substitution. The important advantage of a formal power series ring over a polynomial ring is that it is local (in fact, complete).
Matrix ring and endomorphism ring.
Let "R" be a ring (not necessarily commutative). The set of all square matrices of size "n" with entries in "R" forms a ring with the entry-wise addition and the usual matrix multiplication. It is called the matrix ring and is denoted by M"n"("R"). Given a right "R"-module formula_133, the set of all "R"-linear maps from "U" to itself forms a ring with addition that is of function and multiplication that is of composition of functions; it is called the endomorphism ring of "U" and is denoted by formula_134.
As in linear algebra, a matrix ring may be canonically interpreted as an endomorphism ring: formula_135. This is a special case of the following fact: If formula_136 is an "R"-linear map, then "f" may be written as a matrix with entries formula_137 in formula_138, resulting in the ring isomorphism:
Any ring homomorhism "R" → "S" induces M"n"("R") → M"n"("S"); in fact, any ring homomorphism between matrix rings arises in this way.
Schur's lemma says that if "U" is a simple right "R"-module, then formula_134 is a division ring. If formula_141 is a direct sum of "m""i"-copies of simple "R"-modules formula_142, then 
The Artin–Wedderburn theorem states any semisimple ring (cf. below) is of this form.
A ring "R" and the matrix ring M"n"("R") over it are Morita equivalent: the category of right modules of "R" is equivalent to the category of right modules over M"n"("R"). In particular, two-sided ideals in "R" correspond in one-to-one to two-sided ideals in M"n"("R").
